<p>Maybe because you can't. That's the reason default parameters are designed to guard against <code>undefined</code> values.</p>

<p>As per Mozilla <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Functions/Default_parameters" rel="noreferrer">documentation</a></p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Default function parameters allow named parameters to be initialized
  with default values if no value or undefined is passed</p>
</blockquote>

<p>See above. It's clearly written: if <code>undefined</code> is passed, <code>default</code> parameters are used.</p>
